'Ihis ode is altogether singular among the lyrics of Aristophanes in respect to the number oi logaoedic cola that occur in it. On logaoedics in the ancient sense, see p. 1. Here these are mainly catalectic tetra- podies (1-4‚ 13, 16-18) oi the same value in time as the interspersed Pherecrateans and iambies. On the trochaic opening oi cola 14, 17, see Arist. Quint, p. 32, 37 f. and 33, 30 ff. (Jahn). The logaoedic movement at the close of the lyric (19, ao) is ascending (anapaestic).

In 115ο Bothe corrected θεμιτὸν (R) ; in 1158 Reisig ἀφίκεσθον ( ).

G. Hermann (Epirotae, p. 171, ci. Elementa Dect. Met, p. 541) by numerous changes oi the text attempted to establish correspondence of ode and antode between parts of this lyric. See also Reisig, Coniec- taneorum libri duo, pp. xxi ff. and 302 ff.
